    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">A Study on Role of NVOCC in Shipping Industry with Reference to Chennai Port</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Manikandan. M</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Shipping Industry<br />Chennai Port</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">May-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P5792</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Enactment of the Ocean Shipping Reform Act of 1998 in the United States, together with dramatic changes in the economic condition and competitive structure of the liner container sector of the maritime industry and the advent of Internet-based transaction channels, poses new challenges and opportunities for non-vessel operating common carriers (NVOCC's) in their role as intermediaries in ocean freight markets. Continued viability for NVOCC's will require that they make greater investments in information technology and other supply-chain management
tools and processes, which will raise the value of their services above that of their traditional selling point-cheaper rates.
The role of the middleman or intermediary in commerce is a crucial, if little understood, aspect of economic life. Basic activities of commerce such as finding trade possibilities, assessing the true characteristics or qualities of goods and service providers, negotiating exchange contracts, and other value added services have usually been performed more economically by reliance on middlemen. Recent innovations in technology, such as electronic information via the Internet that makes it easier for customers to interface directly with suppliers, suggest that the middlemen between the ultimate buyer and seller may disappear or evolve into a new form of specialized intermediary. Middlemen traditionally have functioned as brokers, trade specialists, and consolidators and are favored when customers prefer a selection of goods and services with specialized distribution, coverage, and expertise. Competition between middlemen reduces the spread between their buying and selling prices to one that covers just the cost of providing their services at the quality consumers want. If the spread is large, more middlemen will be attracted into the industry that will shave margins to retain business. Only those middlemen who can supply satisfactory services at the lowest cost will survive in the long run.
Non-vessel-operating common carriers (NVOCC's) are considered to be one of the &quot;intermediaries&quot; within the maritime industry. Recent legislation has defined the NVOCC as &quot;a common carrier that does not operate the vessels by which the ocean transportation is provided, and is a shipper in its relationship with the ocean carrier.&quot; In simple terms, NVOCC operators (or NVO's, as they are more commonly known) buy space from ocean carriers for consolidated shipments from a variety of clients. Warehousing, documentation, and logistical planning for cargo from the port to final destination may also be arranged as part of the services provided. Advantages thought to be provided by NVO's are often cheaper rates than ocean carriers, a wider menu of services, and filling a required niche in global commerce as transport providers for smaller shippers.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/10802">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/10802</a></td></tr>
